 Araldite<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">\u00ae<\/span><span> 2-part epoxy resin 50:50 on a disposable surface e.g. weighing boat. Using a pipette tip transfer a small amount of the mixed epoxy to the centre of the teflon (use tip as a capillary to help bring up the glue).<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1049515,"guid":"47B83D900CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","previous_id":1049514,"previous_guid":"47B557600CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"36C5C9B8D9D74302905F3DF95A5CC5C7","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Preparation of Mica Substrate"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"739123DC95C84BEAB868293610D30218","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Cleave the 6 mm mica disc on one side with scotch tape. With the cleaved mica disc facing down, immediately place on top of the epoxy droplet and press flat.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1049516,"guid":"47BBE7100CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","previous_id":1049515,"previous_guid":"47B83D900CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"81888E7B2E004D6AABAAD785D816F390","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Preparation of Mica Substrate"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"8428896D150B4838BBA3FF7949089A8A","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Leave the glue to dry and cure <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"6F5589700CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":0,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1049517,"guid":"47BFB7A00CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","previous_id":1049516,"previous_guid":"47BBE7100CB611EBA88B9F96490C2419","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"87D09EF48A8444BC8E8D1B1D2F9BFE0C","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Preparation of Mica Substrate"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"2B2F0018E2B54B04A81824891F731678","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Once cured, cleave the mica using Scotch tape to reveal an atomically flat clean substrate (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">see<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;\"> <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Note<\/span><span> 8).<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">This is part 1 of the \"Atomic Force Microscopy of DNA and DNA-Protein Interactions\" collection of protocols.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Collection Abstract:<\/span><span> Atomic force microscopy (AFM) is a microscopy technique that uses a sharp probe to trace a sample surface at nanometre resolution. For biological applications, one of its key advantages is its ability to visualize substructure of single molecules and molecular complexes in an aqueous environment. Here, we describe the application of AFM to determine the secondary and tertiary structure of surface-bound DNA, and it\u2019s interactions with proteins.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1603893866}